  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is propolis and how does it support immunity?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Propolis is a resinous mixture that honeybees produce by combining tree sap, beeswax, and their own enzymes. Bees use propolis to seal, sterilize, and protect the hive from pathogens — it functions as the hive\'s immune system. Propolis contains over 300 bioactive compounds including caffeic acid phenethyl ester (CAPE), flavonoids (chrysin, pinocembrin, galangin), phenolic acids, and terpenes. These compounds demonstrate antibacterial, antiviral, antifungal, anti-inflammatory, and immunomodulatory properties in laboratory and clinical studies. CAPE in particular inhibits NF-kB (reducing inflammation), activates immune cells (macrophages, NK cells), and has direct antimicrobial activity against a broad spectrum of bacteria and viruses. Clinical trials show propolis supplementation reduces the frequency and duration of upper respiratory infections.' } },
